{
  "family": "Pinner Reaction",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CC#N",
      "CCO"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(=[NH2+])OCC.[Cl-]"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction represents the classical Pinner reaction, showing the formation of an imino ether hydrochloride salt (a Pinner salt) from a simple aliphatic nitrile (acetonitrile) and an alcohol (ethanol) under anhydrous acidic conditions (HCl). This is the quintessential first step of the Pinner synthesis, which can then be hydrolyzed to an ester or reacted with ammonia/amines to form amidines. The chosen reactants are small, acyclic, and devoid of complex functional groups, making it a clear and unambiguous example of the core transformation.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The reactants are simple aliphatic molecules (acetonitrile and ethanol) to avoid overlap with reactions involving aromatic systems (e.g., Gattermann, Houben-Hoesch) or more complex functional groups. The product is explicitly shown as the characteristic imino ether salt, which is the key intermediate defining the Pinner reaction, distinguishing it from simple nitrile hydrolysis or other nitrile addition reactions."
  }
}
